Model conversion. Conversion conicalâcircular. Fig. 11 describes conversion of a conical model L = {pi } to a circular model K = {qi }. We select one seed point, say q1 (u) on the ruling p1 (u) â¨ p2 (u); the curve q1 shall orthogonally intersect all rulings of the strip L1 which is bounded by p1 , p2 . L1 is enveloped by the cones Î2 (u), and each cone carries a circle c2 (u) which touches the curve q1 in the point q1 (u). Now the adjacent strip L2 , which is bounded by p2 p3 , is enveloped by the same cones Î2 ; in L2 the circles c2 (u) determine another envelope curve q2 orthogonally intersecting the rulings. By construction, distances q1 (u) â p2 (u) and q2 (u) â p2 (u) are equal. This mapping of curves q1 â q2 can be iterated and yields the full model K.

Remark: The principal curvature lines of Ci are known: they are the circular arcs where the generating spheres Î£i (u) touch Ci , together with their orthogonal trajectories (including curves qi and qi+1 ). Therefore approximation of a surface by a conical model and subsequent conversion to a canal surface model achieves a âprincipal patch assemblyâ according to of R. Martin et al. [1986]. The principal strip models have properties important for the segmentation of strips into panels. For that purpose, the angle between rulings and edge curves is important. For both circular and conical models, this angle is near 90 degrees. In the following we discuss approximate segmentation of a principal model into pieces of right circular cones, and into pieces of Dupin cyclides. Results are shown by Fig. 14.
Applications to panelization.

e Conversion circularâconical: Construct a Gauss image K to a given circular model K, and consider the circles ei (u) and ci (u), c which are inscribed in the respective strips of these models. By e construction, ei (u) lies in S 2 and there is a unique cone Îi (u) c which touches S 2 along ei (u). It is not difï¬cult to see that parc e allel translating Îi (u) such that it passes through c2 (u) yields the cones Îi (u) of a conical model L.
Optimization of convertible models. Conversion of the conical model L = {pi } into a circular model K = {qi } (Fig. 11) starts with a seed point, which determines the entire curve q1 , and in turn all other edge curves qi . This represents one degree of freedom. It is easy to associate circular models with a conical one, but the way of conversion renders it unstable with respect to perturbations of the initial data, and there is no guarantee that the orthogonal trajectories qi stay within the strips bounded by pi , pi+1 . We therefore add further terms to the target functional (5): fmiddle favoring the 1 curves 2 (pk + pk+1 ) as orthogonal trajectories, and fwidth , which penalizes uneven strip widths: E2 X Z D Ë Ë fmiddle = pi â pi+1 , pi + pi+1 du, i X Z fwidth = ( pi â pi+1 â pi+1 â pi+2 )2 du.
